# Testing Documentation Instructions

## Documenting Test Coverage

- List what is tested and what is not in a testing section or file
- Group tests by feature or module for easier navigation
- Note any known gaps with a plan or issue reference
- Keep test documentation close to the feature it covers

## Test Examples in Documentation

- Include runnable examples when documenting public APIs
- Show both input and expected output
- Use fenced code blocks with the correct language identifier
- Verify examples still work when updating documentation

## CI and Automation Docs

- Document how to run tests locally (e.g., `make test`)
- List available test-related Makefile or script targets
- Explain CI workflow steps in workflow YAML or a docs/ file
- Document required environment variables or setup steps

## Test Result Formatting

- Use plain-text status markers: `[PASS]`, `[FAIL]`, `[SKIP]`
- Do not use emoji in test output (see `emoji-prevention.md`)
- Present results in tables when summarizing multiple checks
- Include counts: total, passed, failed, skipped


